00:00:40,300 --> 00:00:43,053
Joel Levison's office.

6
00:00:43,136 --> 00:00:45,931
No, I'm sorry, he's not in yet.
May I take a message?

7
00:00:46,807 --> 00:00:49,727
- Yes, Mr. Levy, I'll tell him you called.
- Sandy, never say that.

8
00:00:49,810 --> 00:00:53,021
He's either in conference, in a meeting.
He's always in.

9
00:00:53,105 --> 00:00:55,440
- Now, who was that?
- A Larry Levy?

10
00:00:55,524 --> 00:00:56,942
Great.

11
00:00:57,025 --> 00:00:59,319
I hope there was nothing
in the trades this morning. Was there?

12
00:00:59,402 --> 00:01:01,780
- Well, I don't know. The mail's late.
- Well, go get 'em.

13
00:01:01,863 --> 00:01:05,617
Now! I want them back here
before he arrives.

14
00:01:20,882 --> 00:01:23,260
Griffin. Griffin, hi.

15
00:01:23,343 --> 00:01:25,053
Griffin, hi. A-A-Adam Simon.

16
00:01:25,137 --> 00:01:28,474
- We're not supposed to meet till next week, but
— - I didn't realize we were meeting next week.

17
00:01:28,557 --> 00:01:31,435
Well, I just wanted to plant the seed
in your head just now so that...

18
00:01:31,518 --> 00:01:33,479
I'm booked up.
I can't hear a pitch right now.

19
00:01:33,562 --> 00:01:36,857
Picture this. It's a planet in the far,
far future, a planet with two suns.

20
00:01:36,940 --> 00:01:39,401
- Who plays the sons?
- No, no. Suns. Large solar disks.

21
00:01:39,484 --> 00:01:41,403
Listen, run this idea by Bonnie Sherow.

22
00:01:41,486 --> 00:01:44,656
Pictures they make these days
are all MTV. Cut, cut, cut, cut.

23
00:01:44,739 --> 00:01:48,410
The opening shot of Welles' <i>Touch of Evil</i>
was six and a half minutes long.

24
00:01:48,493 --> 00:01:50,704
- Six and a half minutes, Walter?
- Well, three or four.

25
00:01:50,787 --> 00:01:54,040
He set up the whole picture
with that one tracking shot.

26
00:01:54,124 --> 00:01:56,543
My father was the key grip on that shoot.

27
00:01:56,626 --> 00:02:00,589
Hey, what about <i>Absolute Beginners?</i>
Man, that was an extraordinary shot.

28
00:02:00,672 --> 00:02:02,591
What the hell was that?
Never heard of it.

29
00:02:02,674 --> 00:02:04,802
It was Julian Temple.
It's an English film, Walter.

30
00:02:04,885 --> 00:02:08,597
We're talking about American movies,
and Orson Welles was a master.

31
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:11,516
- Pellegrino, please.
- I've got Calistoga.

32
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:13,685
- Buck, how are ya?
- Good. How ya doin'?

33
00:02:13,768 --> 00:02:15,979
Good.
What do you got for me?

34
00:02:16,062 --> 00:02:18,231
Okay, here it is.

35
00:02:18,315 --> 00:02:20,358
<i>The Graduate Part Two.</i>

36
00:02:20,442 --> 00:02:21,985
- Oh, good. Good.
- Now, listen.

37
00:02:22,068 --> 00:02:24,196
The three principals are still with us...

38
00:02:24,279 --> 00:02:27,157
Dustin Hoffman, Anne Bancroft,
Katharine Ross.

39
00:02:27,240 --> 00:02:28,533
Mm-hmm.

40
00:02:28,617 --> 00:02:30,953
Twenty-five years later.
And so are the characters.

41
00:02:31,036 --> 00:02:34,706
Ben, Elaine and Mrs. Robinson.

42
00:02:34,789 --> 00:02:36,791
Ben and Elaine are married, still.

43
00:02:36,875 --> 00:02:41,379
They live in a big, old, spooky house
up in Northern California somewhere.

44
00:02:41,463 --> 00:02:44,674
- And Mrs. Robinson lives with them.
- Mmm.

45
00:02:44,758 --> 00:02:48,053
Her aging mother, who's had a stroke...

46
00:02:48,136 --> 00:02:49,679
Mrs. Robinson's had a stroke?

47
00:02:49,763 --> 00:02:51,682
Mrs. Robinson's had a stroke,
so she can't talk.

48
00:02:51,765 --> 00:02:53,684
- Is this gonna be funny?
- Yeah, it'll be funny. Dark.

49
00:02:53,767 --> 00:02:56,007
- With a stroke?
- And weird and funny and with a stroke.

50
00:02:56,061 --> 00:02:57,771
- Okay.
- Maybe it's not a stroke.

51
00:02:57,854 --> 00:02:59,773
- Maybe it's — I don't know what it is.
- Anyway, go on.

52
00:02:59,856 --> 00:03:01,233
- It's a malady of some sort.
- Okay.

53
00:03:01,316 --> 00:03:04,736
She's up there in the bedroom upstairs,
listening to everything that happens.

54
00:03:04,819 --> 00:03:06,905
They've got a daughter
who's just graduated from college.

55
00:03:06,988 --> 00:03:08,490
That's good. Young blood.

56
00:03:08,573 --> 00:03:10,159
Twenty-two, twenty-three-year-old.

57
00:03:10,242 --> 00:03:12,161
- Like a Julia Roberts.
- Julia Roberts. Great, great, great.

58
00:03:12,244 --> 00:03:14,663
Excuse me. What did you want me
to do with these scripts?

59
00:03:14,746 --> 00:03:16,186
- That goes to Bonnie Sherow.
- Okay.

60
00:03:16,248 --> 00:03:20,002
And, uh, find out from studio security how
Adam Simon got on the lot. I wanna know.

61
00:03:20,085 --> 00:03:22,170
Okay. Adam Simon? Okay.

62
00:03:22,963 --> 00:03:24,381
- Okay?
- Yes, go ahead.

63
00:03:24,464 --> 00:03:26,550
Julia Roberts comes home.
Their daughter. The graduate.

64
00:03:26,633 --> 00:03:28,051
Yes. The new graduate.

65
00:03:28,134 --> 00:03:29,553
- Th-The new graduate.
- The postgraduate.

66
00:03:29,636 --> 00:03:31,763
Griffin loved it.
He just wanted me to run it by you.

67
00:03:31,846 --> 00:03:34,975
- It's a hardy band of human survivors.
- Listen, write this down for me. Okay?

68
00:03:35,058 --> 00:03:37,269
They have no history, only mythology.
They've lost all technological knowledge.

69
00:03:37,352 --> 00:03:40,564
I can't process any of this unless you
write it down. Could you write it down?

70
00:03:40,647 --> 00:03:42,807
- It's not about words. You gotta visualize it.
- Whoa!

71
00:03:42,857 --> 00:03:45,193
Oh, man.

72
00:03:46,778 --> 00:03:48,488
Jimmy?

73
00:03:48,571 --> 00:03:50,949
- Jimmy, are you okay? What happened?
- You gotta look where you're going.

74
00:03:51,032 --> 00:03:52,952
- Twenty-five words or less?
- Are you all right?

75
00:03:53,034 --> 00:03:54,953
I'd say. My name is Jimmy Chase.

76
00:03:55,036 --> 00:03:56,955
- Are you all right? Open your eyes.
- Huh?

77
00:03:57,038 --> 00:04:00,292
- Are you okay?
- He came outta nowhere, ran into the car.

78
00:04:00,375 --> 00:04:02,544
- I never saw the guy coming.
- It's okay.

79
00:04:04,170 --> 00:04:05,672
Yeah, it's okay.

80
00:04:05,755 --> 00:04:07,632
Hey, that's Adam Simon.

81
00:04:07,716 --> 00:04:09,843
How ya doin', kid?
I was just having a...

82
00:04:09,926 --> 00:04:11,637
- You all right?
- Yeah, it was good.

83
00:04:11,720 --> 00:04:13,513
You sure you're okay?

84
00:04:18,184 --> 00:04:21,604
Rebecca De Mornay.
Actually, you're much better looking.

85
00:04:21,688 --> 00:04:23,773
Um, no.
No, I'm not Rebecca De Mornay.

86
00:04:23,857 --> 00:04:26,276
- Dead ringer.
- Thank you. Thank you very much.

87
00:04:26,359 --> 00:04:29,195
Hey, do you know where
Joel Levison's office is?

88
00:04:29,279 --> 00:04:32,157
<i>The</i> Mr. Levison?
Head of the studio? Yeah.

89
00:04:32,240 --> 00:04:34,240
It's quite, quite moving.
It'll rip your heart out.

90
00:04:34,284 --> 00:04:38,788
This is the area where we make decisions to
give a green light to a picture like that.

91
00:04:38,872 --> 00:04:41,667
Right here. We're gonna go
about 17 stories high, if we can.

92
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:44,002
We're going to continue
using all the Sony products.

93
00:04:44,085 --> 00:04:46,671
<i>Domo arigato</i> to the Sony products, really.

94
00:04:46,755 --> 00:04:51,176
In fact, if you need someone to eat sashimi
with you, you give me a ring, because...

95
00:04:51,259 --> 00:04:52,677
Here's Levison, right here.

96
00:04:52,761 --> 00:04:56,111
- Come with me to my office.
- I have to know that you're seeing it.

97
00:04:57,307 --> 00:04:59,893
- Good girl.
- Traffic from Malibu was impossible.

98
00:04:59,976 --> 00:05:01,478
- Morning, Joel.
- Morning, Celia.

99
00:05:01,561 --> 00:05:03,772
- Sandy, park the car, please.
- Okay.

100
00:05:03,855 --> 00:05:06,608
- Morning, Marty, Annie, Frank.
- Hi.

101
00:05:07,692 --> 00:05:09,194
What are those Japs doing here?

102
00:05:09,277 --> 00:05:12,197
What's all this talk going
around here about heads will roll?

103
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:13,949
The bank's putting the screws to us.

104
00:05:14,032 --> 00:05:17,119
Harvey Goldman's son's coming out
from Boston and I don't like it.

105
00:05:17,202 --> 00:05:20,330
Reggie Goldman's a pip-squeak.
It can't be serious.

106
00:05:20,413 --> 00:05:23,833
- Quite an actor, though.
- Some changes are going on around here.

107
00:05:23,917 --> 00:05:27,837
It's always the way. Happened
at Paramount three years ago.

108
00:05:27,921 --> 00:05:30,131
Columbia's going through it now.

109
00:05:30,215 --> 00:05:32,384
I hear we're looking to replace Griffin.

110
00:05:32,467 --> 00:05:33,718
- Griffin?
- Mm-hmm.

111
00:05:33,802 --> 00:05:37,055
- I don't believe it. With who?
- Berg. Kirkpatrick. Maybe Larry Levy.

112
00:05:37,138 --> 00:05:38,515
Yeah.

113
00:05:38,598 --> 00:05:42,143
Yeah, well, I want to know
why the security is so lax. That's why.

114
00:05:42,227 --> 00:05:45,147
I'll talk to you about it later.
I'm in the middle of a pitch. Okay.

115
00:05:45,230 --> 00:05:47,440
- Listen, go ahead.
- Yeah, okay, okay.

116
00:05:47,524 --> 00:05:50,444
- A TV star goes on safari in Africa.
- Like a Donna Mills or a Joan Collins.

117
00:05:50,527 --> 00:05:53,446
You're talking about a TV star
in a major motion picture?

118
00:05:53,530 --> 00:05:55,574
No, not a real TV star.
It would be played by a movie star.

119
00:05:55,657 --> 00:05:56,575
A movie star playing a television star
in a major motion picture.

120
00:05:56,658 --> 00:06:01,246
- Goldie, Julia, Michelle, Bette, Lily, Dolly.
- Julia Roberts. Dolly Parton would be good.

121
00:06:01,329 --> 00:06:03,915
You know, I — I like Goldie.
I like Goldie.

122
00:06:03,998 --> 00:06:06,585
- Great. 'Cause we have a relationship.
<i>- Goldie Goes to Africa.</i>

123
00:06:06,668 --> 00:06:07,586
That would be great.

124
00:06:07,669 --> 00:06:10,005
<i>- Goldie Goes to Africa.
- Goldie Goes to Africa.</i>

125
00:06:10,088 --> 00:06:12,090
- And she becomes worshipped.
- Worshipped?

126
00:06:12,173 --> 00:06:13,813
- Well, she's found by this tribe —
- Yes?

127
00:06:13,883 --> 00:06:16,803
Of small people. But then
she has to go back to her life.

128
00:06:16,886 --> 00:06:18,972
She's found by this tribe
and they worship her.

129
00:06:19,055 --> 00:06:21,433
Oh, I see. It's kind of like
a <i>Gods Must Be Crazy,</i>

130
00:06:21,516 --> 00:06:23,602
except the Coke bottle's
now a television actress.

131
00:06:23,685 --> 00:06:26,021
Yeah, it's exactly right.
It's <i>Out of Africa</i> meets <i>Pretty Woman.</i>

132
00:06:26,104 --> 00:06:28,440
- Well, but you know what?
- She has to decide whether...

133
00:06:28,523 --> 00:06:30,442
- You know what we could do?
- To stay with the TV show

134
00:06:30,525 --> 00:06:33,153
- or save this entire African tribe.
- It could be a man.

135
00:06:33,236 --> 00:06:35,530
- Hey, where's Griffin Mill's office?
- Right here.

136
00:06:35,613 --> 00:06:38,533
- Hey, you're Martin Scorsese.
- No, but I know Harvey Keitel.

137
00:06:38,616 --> 00:06:42,120
Yeah, I know you do.
Hey, I loved <i>Cape Fear.</i>

138
00:06:42,203 --> 00:06:43,997
My old man worked for Hitchcock too.

139
00:06:44,080 --> 00:06:47,125
- Yeah?
<i>- Rope.</i> It was a masterpiece.

140
00:06:47,208 --> 00:06:50,128
Story wasn't any good.
He shot the whole thing without cuts.

141
00:06:50,211 --> 00:06:52,130
I hate all this cut, cut, cut.

142
00:06:52,213 --> 00:06:54,340
Oh, yeah, well, what about Bertolucci?

143
00:06:54,424 --> 00:06:57,302
That great tracking shot with Winger
in <i>Sheltering Sky?</i>

144
00:06:57,385 --> 00:06:58,761
I didn't see it.

145
00:07:01,139 --> 00:07:03,225
<i>Touch of Evil,</i> that was the one.
Welles, Hitchcock...

146
00:07:03,308 --> 00:07:05,602
- I've been here since 8:00.
- You were in the commissary, Whitney.

147
00:07:05,685 --> 00:07:08,230
I stuck my neck out for you to
get this job. Who were you with?

148
00:07:08,313 --> 00:07:12,984
- I-I was in there with, um, A-Alan Rudolph.
- What were you doing with Alan Rudolph?

149
00:07:13,067 --> 00:07:16,321
He asked me to have coffee
and he was telling me this idea he had.

150
00:07:16,404 --> 00:07:19,004
Whitney, you're my assistant.
You don't get involved with writers.

151
00:07:19,032 --> 00:07:21,785
I wasn't getting involved. I was just
listening to this amazing idea he had.

152
00:07:21,868 --> 00:07:24,548
- I told him he should give it to you.
- What's your pitch?

153
00:07:24,579 --> 00:07:26,247
Well, does political scare you?

154
00:07:26,331 --> 00:07:29,501
Political doesn't scare me.
Radical political scares me.

155
00:07:29,584 --> 00:07:31,461
- This is —
<i>- Political</i> political scares me.

156
00:07:31,544 --> 00:07:32,796
<i>Politely</i> politically radical.

157
00:07:32,879 --> 00:07:34,380
- Is it funny?
- It's funny.

158
00:07:34,464 --> 00:07:36,842
- It's a funny political thing.
- And it's a thriller too.

159
00:07:36,925 --> 00:07:38,801
- It's a thriller?
- And all at once.

160
00:07:38,885 --> 00:07:41,513
- So, uh, what's the story?
- Well, I want Bruce Willis.

161
00:07:41,596 --> 00:07:43,264
I think I can talk to him.

162
00:07:43,348 --> 00:07:46,476
It's a story about a senator.
A bad-guy senator, at first.

163
00:07:46,559 --> 00:07:49,187
He's traveling around the country
on the country's dime, you know,

164
00:07:49,270 --> 00:07:50,855
like that Sununu guy used to.

165
00:07:50,939 --> 00:07:53,483
I see. So it's sort of
a cynical, political thriller-comedy?

166
00:07:53,566 --> 00:07:56,027
Yeah, but it's got a heart,
uh, in the right spot.

167
00:07:56,110 --> 00:07:58,530
And, anyway, he has an accident.

168
00:07:58,613 --> 00:08:01,616
- An accident?
- Yeah, and he becomes clairvoyant.

169
00:08:01,699 --> 00:08:03,743
- Like a psychic.
- Oh, I see.

170
00:08:03,826 --> 00:08:06,913
So it's kind of a psychic,
political thriller-comedy with a heart.

171
00:08:06,996 --> 00:08:08,456
With a heart.

172
00:08:08,540 --> 00:08:11,251
Not unlike <i>Ghost</i>
meets <i>Manchurian Candidate.</i>

173
00:08:11,334 --> 00:08:14,837
- Go on, go on, I'm listening.
- Anyway, he can read people's minds.

174
00:08:14,921 --> 00:08:18,216
And when he gets to the president's mind,
it's completely blank.

175
00:08:18,299 --> 00:08:20,635
- Completely blank!
- Can I get you anything?

176
00:08:20,718 --> 00:08:22,929
- I'd like a beer, please.
- We don't have beer.

177
00:08:23,012 --> 00:08:25,348
Uh, okay, wine.
Red wine, please.

178
00:08:26,933 --> 00:08:30,883
Of course someone gets killed at the end.
They always do in political thrillers.

179
00:08:32,105 --> 00:08:35,025
- Griffin Mill's office.
<i>- Yeah, I know that. Can you put him on?</i>

180
00:08:35,108 --> 00:08:37,861
- It's an intriguing idea, Jim.
- May I ask who's calling, please?

181
00:08:37,944 --> 00:08:40,155
<i>- Griffin Mill, please.</i>
- We gotta get somebody really dangerous.

182
00:08:40,238 --> 00:08:42,824
- Well, he's in a meeting right now.
- You know, Bruce Willis or Mel Gibson.

183
00:08:42,907 --> 00:08:44,576
- Great. Let me get back to you.
- Thanks.

184
00:08:44,659 --> 00:08:46,244
- Excuse me, sir.
<i>- Bullshit, lady.</i>

185
00:08:46,327 --> 00:08:48,163
<i>- He'll get back to me?</i>
- Seen my Binaca anywhere?

186
00:08:48,246 --> 00:08:50,582
<i>Do you know how many times
I have heard that?</i>

187
00:08:50,665 --> 00:08:52,876
- Who is this?
<i>- If he don't get back to me, tell him —</i>

188
00:08:52,959 --> 00:08:54,878
- Griffin, I read that script.
- Who was that?

189
00:08:54,961 --> 00:08:57,547
- I don't know. He didn't say.
- It's a nice idea. Just maybe a little soft.

190
00:08:57,630 --> 00:08:59,549
I don't know how you're
gonna cast it through.

191
00:08:59,632 --> 00:09:03,094
The lead character is a 50-year-old
female circus performer. A fire-eater.

192
00:09:03,177 --> 00:09:05,388
Let me read the coverage.

193
00:09:05,471 --> 00:09:08,350
- Are we still having lunch with Aaron Camp?
- Yeah. What time?

194
00:09:08,433 --> 00:09:10,602
I made it for 1:00.

195
00:09:10,685 --> 00:09:13,521
- Bad day?
- He's having writer's block.

196
00:09:15,481 --> 00:09:18,610
Griffin, you have a meeting with Harders
and Frank South this afternoon.

197
00:09:18,693 --> 00:09:20,028
- What time?
- At 3:00.

198
00:09:20,111 --> 00:09:22,405
I'll be here. Put this morning's
meetings in the computer.

199
00:09:22,488 --> 00:09:24,490
- All right.
- Thanks.

200
00:09:24,574 --> 00:09:26,993
- Are you going now?
- No. I'm going to see Levison.

201
00:09:27,076 --> 00:09:30,538
I'll meet you there. Order me
a Caesar salad and Crystal Geyser.

202
00:09:30,622 --> 00:09:33,625
Thanks.

203
00:09:38,963 --> 00:09:40,298
- Okay, by 5:00?
- Mm-hmm.

204
00:09:40,381 --> 00:09:42,133
- Thanks, Sandy.
- Bye.

205
00:09:42,216 --> 00:09:44,678
- Hi, Sandy. Hi, Celia.
- Griffin, you can't go in there.

206
00:09:44,761 --> 00:09:46,262
He's in a meeting.

207
00:09:46,346 --> 00:09:48,848
So I think, you know,
dime-a-dozen out here, don't you?

208
00:09:48,931 --> 00:09:51,267
- It's all right, Celia.
- You know this one?

209
00:09:51,351 --> 00:09:55,313
I don't think you've met Reg Goldman.
You know his father, Harvey.

210
00:09:55,396 --> 00:09:58,900
Yes, of course. Hi, Reg.
From the bank in Boston. Right.

211
00:09:58,983 --> 00:10:01,069
Reg is out here for a couple of weeks.

212
00:10:01,152 --> 00:10:02,654
Great.

213
00:10:02,737 --> 00:10:05,907
- Business or pleasure?
- A little of both, I hope.

214
00:10:06,741 --> 00:10:09,077
Reg is thinking of getting
into production, Griffin.

215
00:10:09,160 --> 00:10:10,912
Oh, really?

216
00:10:10,995 --> 00:10:13,498
Yeah. Beats work.
Doesn't it, Griffin?

217
00:10:13,581 --> 00:10:15,958
Like to play tennis though.
