00:37:20,081 --> 00:37:22,083
I said let's forget this.

687
00:37:27,213 --> 00:37:29,382
Aw, shit.

688
00:37:31,467 --> 00:37:33,469
Mill, you okay?

689
00:37:33,553 --> 00:37:35,138
You all right?

690
00:37:42,103 --> 00:37:43,563
Keep it to yourself!

691
00:37:44,981 --> 00:37:47,150
Keep it to yourself!

692
00:37:47,650 --> 00:37:49,402
Keep it to yourself.

693
00:38:13,259 --> 00:38:14,761
Kahane?

694
00:39:35,174 --> 00:39:37,135
<i>You know what's interesting.</i>

695
00:39:37,218 --> 00:39:39,429
<i>I mean, who —
Who's writing this new ending?</i>

696
00:39:39,512 --> 00:39:41,931
<i>Who wrote the new ending
of</i> Fatal Attraction? <i>The audience.</i>

697
00:39:42,014 --> 00:39:43,433
<i>In that case —</i>

698
00:39:43,516 --> 00:39:45,477
<i>A million-plus screenwriters,
and the audience wrote that ending.</i>

699
00:39:45,560 --> 00:39:49,397
<i>Yes, but who's to say what it would have
done if you had left the original ending?</i>

700
00:39:49,480 --> 00:39:51,399
<i>- You can't say.
- You're right. You can't say.</i>

701
00:39:51,482 --> 00:39:54,027
<i>But you</i> can <i>say that it's done
almost 300 million worldwide</i>

702
00:39:54,110 --> 00:39:56,960
<i>with the ending that was selected
from the test screening.</i>

703
00:39:57,280 --> 00:40:00,325
Larry Levy, I don't believe that you've
met my assistant, Whitney Gersh.

704
00:40:00,408 --> 00:40:02,577
- No, I haven't.
- It's a great pleasure to meet you.

705
00:40:02,660 --> 00:40:05,079
Nice to meet you, Whitney.

706
00:40:05,163 --> 00:40:07,082
- What are you doing?
- Bonnie, how's your picture doing?

707
00:40:07,165 --> 00:40:09,084
- It just tested last week.
- It's doing well.

708
00:40:09,167 --> 00:40:10,585
- How well?
- It was our first test.

709
00:40:10,668 --> 00:40:13,212
- Were you breathing hard?
- Excuse me, Walter.

710
00:40:13,296 --> 00:40:17,800
Um, Joel, Griffin still isn't in, but I
really think we have to start this meeting.

711
00:40:17,884 --> 00:40:20,052
Okay, Celia. Thank you.

712
00:40:22,722 --> 00:40:25,057
You remember a movie called <i>DOA?</i>

713
00:40:25,141 --> 00:40:27,393
Sure I do.
Eddie O'Brien and Pam Britton.

714
00:40:27,477 --> 00:40:30,646
Disney did a remake in '87 or '88.

715
00:40:30,730 --> 00:40:33,650
Yeah, well, I think we got pretty much
the same situation here.

716
00:40:33,733 --> 00:40:35,943
Keep our noses clean, Walter.

717
00:40:36,569 --> 00:40:38,112
I can see you're flush.

718
00:40:40,198 --> 00:40:43,117
It's a shame to waste the picture.
It's a great picture.

719
00:40:43,201 --> 00:40:46,579
Who said we're wasting the picture?
Where did that come from?

720
00:40:46,662 --> 00:40:49,582
You know what's interesting.
We're all too busy to go see movies.

721
00:40:49,665 --> 00:40:52,502
Griffin, you're really late.
They're, like, waiting inside.

722
00:40:52,585 --> 00:40:54,712
- Here's your meeting agenda.
- You oughta try it sometime.

723
00:40:54,795 --> 00:40:57,715
Actually rub shoulders
with the great unwashed.

724
00:40:57,798 --> 00:41:01,177
We need to give them
the kind of pictures they want,

725
00:41:01,260 --> 00:41:03,388
not the kind these writers
want to give them.

726
00:41:03,471 --> 00:41:06,807
I know you guys spend
a lot of time with writers.

727
00:41:06,891 --> 00:41:10,686
Believe me, you have
my deepest sympathy, but...

728
00:41:10,770 --> 00:41:13,898
- Hello. Sorry I'm late.
- You certainly are.

729
00:41:15,233 --> 00:41:17,735
- Jan, talk to you for a minute, please?
- Yeah.

730
00:41:17,818 --> 00:41:21,114
- Just a couple minutes in your office is fine.
- Sure. How you doing?

731
00:41:21,197 --> 00:41:23,575
Griffin, you missed the formal
welcoming ceremony this morning.

732
00:41:23,658 --> 00:41:25,409
You know Larry Levy.

733
00:41:26,577 --> 00:41:27,995
Of course.

734
00:41:28,079 --> 00:41:30,623
- Hi, Larry.
- Hi, Griffin.

735
00:41:30,706 --> 00:41:33,376
Larry was able to get out of Fox
a week earlier than he thought

736
00:41:33,459 --> 00:41:35,586
and has come aboard as of this morning.

737
00:41:35,670 --> 00:41:38,214
Great. Let's, uh — Let's start.

738
00:41:39,382 --> 00:41:41,634
In fact, Larry was just
in the middle of something.

739
00:41:41,717 --> 00:41:43,887
Oh, no. I wasn't. I was just
killing time waiting for Griffin.

740
00:41:43,970 --> 00:41:45,888
Oh. Well, no. Finish.

741
00:41:45,972 --> 00:41:47,890
What were you saying?

742
00:41:47,974 --> 00:41:51,728
I was just saying that I've yet to meet a
writer who could change water into wine,

743
00:41:51,811 --> 00:41:54,772
and we have a tendency
to treat them like that.

744
00:41:54,855 --> 00:41:57,316
Not at this studio.

745
00:41:57,858 --> 00:41:59,986
A million, million and a half
for these scripts.

746
00:42:00,069 --> 00:42:02,113
It's — It's nuts.

747
00:42:02,196 --> 00:42:04,532
And I think avoidable.

748
00:42:04,615 --> 00:42:06,033
Let me ask you something.

749
00:42:06,117 --> 00:42:08,286
When was the last time
you bought a ticket to see a movie?

750
00:42:08,369 --> 00:42:11,372
- You actually paid your own money to see it?
- Last night.

751
00:42:12,415 --> 00:42:14,500
In Pasadena.
<i>The Bicycle Thief.</i>

752
00:42:14,584 --> 00:42:18,129
- You went to see <i>The Bicycle Thief?</i>
- I love that film. It's a great film.

753
00:42:18,212 --> 00:42:21,758
It's an art movie. It doesn't count.
We're talking about "movie" movies.

754
00:42:21,841 --> 00:42:23,301
Jesus, people.

755
00:42:23,384 --> 00:42:25,845
All I'm saying is, there's a lot
of time and money to be saved

756
00:42:25,928 --> 00:42:28,681
if we came up
with these stories on our own.

757
00:42:28,764 --> 00:42:30,683
Where are these stories
coming from, Larry?

758
00:42:30,766 --> 00:42:33,019
Anywhere. Anywhere.
It doesn't matter. Anywhere.

759
00:42:33,102 --> 00:42:35,938
The newspaper.
Pick a story. Any story.

760
00:42:36,022 --> 00:42:37,565
All right.

761
00:42:39,442 --> 00:42:42,612
"Immigrants Protest Budget Cuts
in Literacy Program."

762
00:42:42,695 --> 00:42:46,157
Human spirit overcoming economic adversity.
Sounds like Horatio Alger in the barrio.

763
00:42:46,240 --> 00:42:49,952
Put Jimmy Smits in it and you got
a sexy <i>Stand and Deliver.</i> Next.

764
00:42:50,036 --> 00:42:52,413
- Come on.
- Larry, this isn't my field.

765
00:42:52,496 --> 00:42:55,458
Marty, it doesn't matter.
Just give it a shot. You can't lose here.

766
00:42:55,541 --> 00:42:58,127
Okay.

767
00:42:58,210 --> 00:43:02,381
How about, uh,
"Mud Slide Kills 60 in Slums of Chile."

768
00:43:02,465 --> 00:43:06,260
That's good. Triumph over tragedy.
Sounds like a John Boorman picture.

769
00:43:06,344 --> 00:43:09,347
Slap a happy ending on it,
the script will write itself.

770
00:43:09,430 --> 00:43:11,057
Bon. Here, give me the paper.

771
00:43:11,140 --> 00:43:13,434
Gee, I don't know, <i>Lar.</i>

772
00:43:13,517 --> 00:43:15,227
Give it a shot.

773
00:43:16,937 --> 00:43:20,358
"Further Bond Losses
Push Dow Down 7.15."

774
00:43:21,192 --> 00:43:23,152
I see Connery as Bond.

775
00:43:23,235 --> 00:43:26,195
That's funny. It's a good thing
Oliver Stone wasn't listening to you.

776
00:43:26,238 --> 00:43:27,740
Where would we have been?

777
00:43:27,823 --> 00:43:30,743
Well, we all would have been
spared having to sit through <i>Wall Street.</i>

778
00:43:30,826 --> 00:43:33,162
Marty, what did <i>Wall Street</i> do worldwide?

779
00:43:33,245 --> 00:43:35,665
Seventy, 75, maybe 80.

780
00:43:35,748 --> 00:43:39,126
Eighty million dollars,
a couple of Oscars — nothing to sneeze at.

781
00:43:39,210 --> 00:43:42,254
I think Larry's point is well taken.
Let's move on now.

782
00:43:42,338 --> 00:43:45,788
Griffin, uh, can you give us an update
on the Taylor Hackford project?

783
00:43:46,759 --> 00:43:48,678
Griffin?

784
00:43:48,761 --> 00:43:50,304
Yeah.

785
00:43:51,305 --> 00:43:54,016
I was just thinking
what an interesting concept it is

786
00:43:54,100 --> 00:43:58,270
to eliminate the writer
from the artistic process.

787
00:43:59,355 --> 00:44:03,405
If we can just get rid of these actors and
directors, maybe we got something here.

788
00:44:09,615 --> 00:44:11,283
Hello, Walter.

789
00:44:11,367 --> 00:44:13,369
Make yourself at home.

790
00:44:13,452 --> 00:44:17,456
Mr. Mill, I understand you were
kinda late coming in this morning.

791
00:44:17,540 --> 00:44:19,542
You all right?

792
00:44:19,625 --> 00:44:21,252
I'm fine.

793
00:44:21,335 --> 00:44:23,129
Appreciate your concern.

794
00:44:24,964 --> 00:44:27,341
What can I do for you, Walter?

795
00:44:27,425 --> 00:44:30,636
Don't tell me you came here
to pitch me a story.

796
00:44:30,720 --> 00:44:33,389
That's exactly what I've come to do.

797
00:44:33,472 --> 00:44:36,684
It's a good one too.
It's about a writer. Sort of.

798
00:44:36,767 --> 00:44:38,436
David Kahane.

799
00:44:41,105 --> 00:44:43,357
David Kahane.
Who's David Kahane?

800
00:44:43,441 --> 00:44:44,900
Oh, you met him.

801
00:44:45,818 --> 00:44:48,154
- Well, I meet a lot of writers.
- Uh-huh.

802
00:44:48,237 --> 00:44:50,717
But this particular writer that you met
was murdered last night

803
00:44:50,781 --> 00:44:52,867
in back of the Rialto theater in Pasadena.

804
00:44:52,950 --> 00:44:54,493
Murdered?

805
00:44:54,577 --> 00:44:58,664
Oh, come to think of it,
Pasadena's as good a place to die as any.

806
00:45:00,207 --> 00:45:01,917
So, what's the story?

807
00:45:02,001 --> 00:45:04,003
Twenty-five words or less?

808
00:45:04,086 --> 00:45:05,963
Okay.

809
00:45:06,046 --> 00:45:08,966
Movie exec calls writer. Writer's
girlfriend says he's at the movies.

810
00:45:09,049 --> 00:45:12,261
Exec goes to the movies,
meets writer, drinks with writer.

811
00:45:12,344 --> 00:45:15,848
Writer gets conked and dies
in four inches of dirty water.

812
00:45:15,931 --> 00:45:18,392
Movie exec is in deep shit.

813
00:45:19,518 --> 00:45:21,479
What do you think?

814
00:45:21,562 --> 00:45:23,272
That's more than 25 words.

815
00:45:23,355 --> 00:45:25,065
And it's bullshit.

816
00:45:25,691 --> 00:45:27,819
Yeah, well, Pasadena homicide
doesn't think it's bullshit.

817
00:45:27,902 --> 00:45:29,862
They got a complete report.

818
00:45:29,945 --> 00:45:33,116
You met Kahane at the Rialto. You got
drunk with him at a Japanese restaurant.

819
00:45:33,199 --> 00:45:36,619
He left before you did.
That's the last time anyone saw him alive.

820
00:45:36,702 --> 00:45:38,662
Except you, maybe.

821
00:45:38,746 --> 00:45:41,457
Why are you denying this?

822
00:45:43,209 --> 00:45:45,211
What do the police think?

823
00:45:45,294 --> 00:45:48,047
They think it's a botched robbery.

824
00:45:48,130 --> 00:45:51,050
You know,
the window of his car was busted.

825
00:45:51,133 --> 00:45:54,595
He surprised someone
trying to take the radio.

826
00:45:54,678 --> 00:45:57,056
There was a fight.
He was killed.

827
00:45:57,139 --> 00:45:59,141
I didn't kill him, Walter.

828
00:46:00,226 --> 00:46:02,770
But I went to see him.

829
00:46:02,853 --> 00:46:04,855
I know I said I didn't, but I did.

830
00:46:04,939 --> 00:46:06,982
Why'd you lie to me?

831
00:46:07,066 --> 00:46:10,861
Well... now's not
a very good time for me.

832
00:46:10,945 --> 00:46:13,739
Haven't you heard the rumors?
I'm on my way out.

833
00:46:14,657 --> 00:46:17,326
Just what I need —
A little more controversy.

834
00:46:17,409 --> 00:46:19,411
This is not a good time, Walter.

835
00:46:20,704 --> 00:46:26,544
Look, I am in charge of studio security
in every definition of the word,

836
00:46:26,627 --> 00:46:30,047
which means it is my job
to take care of a studio executive,

837
00:46:30,130 --> 00:46:33,843
should he be, uh, shall we say,
under suspicion of murder

838
00:46:33,926 --> 00:46:38,222
at a time when profits are down and
the company is vulnerable for a takeover.

839
00:46:38,305 --> 00:46:41,475
It is my job to keep this
very, very, very, very quiet!

840
00:46:42,810 --> 00:46:44,937
Do you wanna help?

841
00:46:45,020 --> 00:46:47,898
- Of course.
- Then stop lying.

842
00:46:47,982 --> 00:46:50,609
- How many meetings you have with this guy?
- One.

843
00:46:51,652 --> 00:46:53,780
- Not counting last night?
- Not counting last night.

844
00:46:53,863 --> 00:46:56,657
Why'd you go all the way
to Pasadena to meet him?

845
00:46:56,740 --> 00:46:59,660
He had an idea I was interested in.
I wanted to talk to him right away.

846
00:46:59,743 --> 00:47:02,330
His girlfriend. I guess
she was a friend of yours too.

847
00:47:02,413 --> 00:47:03,998
Think fast!

848
00:47:04,081 --> 00:47:07,209
Jesus Christ, Walter,
what do you think? What is this?

849
00:47:07,293 --> 00:47:10,463
It's the third degree. If you don't like it,
wait till the police start asking questions.

850
00:47:10,546 --> 00:47:14,008
- They'll be a lot less polite than I am!
- I'll go to the police! You come with me!

851
00:47:14,091 --> 00:47:16,385
Now you're acting
like someone's who's guilty.

852
00:47:16,468 --> 00:47:18,429
You're not guilty, are you?

853
00:47:18,512 --> 00:47:20,723
For the last time, I'm not a murderer.

854
00:47:38,073 --> 00:47:39,825
Bad news?

855
00:47:39,909 --> 00:47:41,493
What?

856
00:47:41,577 --> 00:47:44,163
The fax. Is it bad news?

857
00:47:44,246 --> 00:47:45,497
No.

858
00:47:46,916 --> 00:47:48,542
Business as usual.

859
00:47:50,169 --> 00:47:53,839
The Hollywood system
did not murder David Kahane.

860
00:47:53,923 --> 00:47:57,051
Not the 98-million-dollar movie.
Not the 12-million-dollar actor.

861
00:47:57,134 --> 00:48:02,139
Not even the million-dollar deal
that David Kahane never landed.

862
00:48:02,973 --> 00:48:05,809
No, the most that we can pin on Hollywood

863
00:48:05,893 --> 00:48:08,562
is assault with intent to kill.

864
00:48:09,563 --> 00:48:14,401
Because society is responsible
for this particular murder,

865
00:48:14,485 --> 00:48:16,695
and it is to society that we must look

866
00:48:16,779 --> 00:48:20,282
if we are to have any justice
for that crime.

867
00:48:20,366 --> 00:48:23,285
Because someone in the night

868
00:48:23,369 --> 00:48:25,329
killed David Kahane,

869
00:48:25,412 --> 00:48:27,998
and that person
will have to bear the guilt.

870
00:48:29,333 --> 00:48:32,002
And if, uh, David were here right now,

871
00:48:32,086 --> 00:48:34,686
I know in my heart that —
That he — h-he would say...

872
00:48:36,006 --> 00:48:38,676
"Cut the shit, Phil.

873
00:48:38,759 --> 00:48:42,259
What did you learn from all of this?
Did you learn anything from this?"

874
00:48:42,930 --> 00:48:45,975
And I'd say, "Uh, yeah, David,
uh, I've learned a lot.

875
00:48:46,058 --> 00:48:49,144
We here, uh, we'll take it from here."

876
00:48:49,228 --> 00:48:52,690
And the next time we sell
a script for a million dollars,

877
00:48:53,482 --> 00:48:56,944
the next time we nail some
shit-bag producer to the wall, we'll say,

878
00:48:57,027 --> 00:48:59,029
"That's another one
for David Kahane!"

879
00:49:02,950 --> 00:49:04,952
David was working on something
the day he died.

880
00:49:05,035 --> 00:49:07,579
I'd like to share it with you.

881
00:49:08,330 --> 00:49:09,790
"Blackness.

882
00:49:09,873 --> 00:49:11,375
A mangy dog barks.

883
00:49:12,084 --> 00:49:16,422
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the streets hunt for food.

884
00:49:17,256 --> 00:49:19,758
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock goes off.

885
00:49:19,842 --> 00:49:23,345
Interior. Flophouse room.
Early morning.

886
00:49:23,429 --> 00:49:26,557
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

887
00:49:26,640 --> 00:49:30,185
Light streams in through holes
in the yellowing window shades.

888
00:49:30,269 --> 00:49:33,022
Moths dance in the beams of light.

889
00:49:33,105 --> 00:49:36,358
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

890
00:49:36,442 --> 00:49:39,236
Stop on an old shoe.

891
00:49:39,319 --> 00:49:41,321
It's empty."

892
00:49:45,659 --> 00:49:47,661
That's as far as he got.

893
00:49:48,787 --> 00:49:50,998
That's the last thing he wrote.

894
00:49:52,291 --> 00:49:54,543
So long, Dave.

895
00:49:54,626 --> 00:49:56,712
Fade out.

896
00:49:56,795 --> 00:49:58,338
Thank you.

897
00:50:14,313 --> 00:50:17,316
Who are you?
You're not a writer.

898
00:50:18,734 --> 00:50:21,111
No, I-I'm — I'm G — I'm Griffin Mill.

899
00:50:21,195 --> 00:50:22,905
- We spoke the night David wa —
- Oh.

900
00:50:22,988 --> 00:50:25,908
Blue sea, white sea.

901
00:50:25,991 --> 00:50:28,368
- It turned out you were right.
- What?

902
00:50:28,452 --> 00:50:30,788
It was a red sea.

903
00:50:30,871 --> 00:50:32,998
Oh. Yeah.

904
00:50:34,958 --> 00:50:38,087
You're the only person I know here.

905
00:50:38,170 --> 00:50:41,173
Listen, I'm really sorry about David.

906
00:50:41,256 --> 00:50:44,593
He was, uh... a talent.

907
00:50:45,719 --> 00:50:47,930
You really think so?

908
00:50:48,013 --> 00:50:50,432
I always suspected he was...

909
00:50:51,266 --> 00:50:53,852
uniquely untalented.

910
00:50:55,395 --> 00:50:57,732
But it's nice of you to say that.
It's nice of you to come.

911
00:50:57,815 --> 00:51:00,192
- Really, you didn't have to.
- Well, I did.

912
00:51:00,275 --> 00:51:04,321
You know, I was probably
the last person to see him alive.

913
00:51:04,404 --> 00:51:06,949
Yeah. The police told me.

914
00:51:07,032 --> 00:51:09,076
Well, not quite the last, surely.

915
00:51:09,159 --> 00:51:10,702
No.

916
00:51:12,454 --> 00:51:15,499
I'm sure this is a terrible time for you.

917
00:51:15,582 --> 00:51:17,960
Is there anything you need or...

918
00:51:18,043 --> 00:51:20,212
No, really. I...

919
00:51:20,295 --> 00:51:22,756
I don't feel bad.

920
00:51:22,840 --> 00:51:25,050
It's like when my parents died. I...

921
00:51:25,884 --> 00:51:27,970
